## Do's and Don'ts

### ✅ Do

- Co-locate feature-specific components, hooks, and types within a feature folder when the feature grows large.
- Write self-documenting code — clear variable names over comments.
- Use Server Components by default; only add `"use client"` when you need interactivity or browser APIs.
- Keep API routes thin — logic belongs in service functions.
- Use Zod for all input validation (forms + API).

### ❌ Don't

- Don't `fetch()` directly inside components — use services + React Query (hooks currently use `fetch()` directly; migrate to the service layer as the project grows).
- Don't put business logic inside route handlers.
- Don't use `default export` for anything other than Next.js pages/layouts.
- Don't commit `.env` — only `.env.example`.
- Don't mix server and client concerns in the same file.
- Don't leave unused imports, `console.log`s, or commented-out code in commits.
